<p>1806 July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">were waiting for us from the opposite side sent by La France whom we had dispatched<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Several Young men came over to assist in crossing our horses<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e now paid our host for his trouble board &amp; lodgings &amp;<sup>c</sup>.  Sixty rounds of ammunition four scalping Knives one lb Tobacco five flints two gun worms one dozen ri<span class="DelHand-author">g</span>ngs and one dozen Hawk bills and he was perfectly satisfied.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>t the water side we <span class="DelHand-author">m</span><span class="AddHand-author">w</span>ere met by the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gros Blanc</span> Chief of the great Village<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He ferried M<sup>r</sup> Chaboillez and myself over in his own Canoe.  He invited us to take up our quarters at His hut over which the U S flag was already flying for our reception<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Young men were very expert in managing the horses.  While swimming over they led them by a Cord and notwithstanding the Missisouri is large and the current Strong they drifted very little.  The canoes are of a singular construction<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A Stranger would scarcely trust his life in them to cross such a deep and rapid river.  The<span class="AddHand-author">y</span> are of a circular form the timber consist of bent willows three inches thick over which is streched a raw Buffaloe hide with the <span class="AddHand-author">h</span>air inwards.  The Gunnels are also of willow and equally slender.  It is surprising the weight these slight things</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">can</p>

